\textbf{4.} The dot plot shows the speeds of pitches of a baseball during the second inning of a game.

\begin{tikzpicture}
\draw[<->] (0,0) -- (6,0);
\foreach \x/\label in {0/40, 0.5/45, 1/50, 1.5/55, 2/60, 2.5/65, 3/70, 3.5/75, 4/80, 4.5/85, 5/90, 5.5/95} {
  \draw (\x, -0.1) -- (\x, 0.1);
  \node[below] at (\x, -0.1) {\footnotesize \label};
}
\node[right] at (6,0) {Speed};
\node[right] at (6,-0.4) {(miles per hour)};
% Dots at 45 (x=0.5)
\fill (0.5, 0.3) circle (2pt);
% Dots at 60 (x=2)
\fill (2, 0.3) circle (2pt);
\fill (2.2, 0.3) circle (2pt);
% Dots at 75 (x=3.5)
\fill (3.5, 0.3) circle (2pt);
\fill (3.5, 0.5) circle (2pt);
% Dots at 80 (x=4)
\fill (4, 0.3) circle (2pt);
\fill (4, 0.5) circle (2pt);
% Dots at 85 (x=4.5)
\fill (4.5, 0.3) circle (2pt);
\fill (4.5, 0.5) circle (2pt);
% Dots at 90 (x=5)
\fill (5, 0.3) circle (2pt);
\fill (5, 0.5) circle (2pt);
\end{tikzpicture}

\textbf{a.} Find and interpret the number of data values on the dot plot.

\textbf{b.} How can you collect these data? What are the units?

\textbf{c.} Write a statistical question that you can answer using the dot plot. Then answer the question.
